DOCUMENT();
loadMacros('PGstandard.pl', 'PGML.pl', 'parserPopUp.pl', 'PGcourse.pl');

Context("Numeric");
Context()->variables->add(w => "Real");

## set the base cost and slope, then calculate the values for the two points we give
$b = random(20, 80, 5);
$m = random(2,  20, 2);

$w1 = 100;
$c1 = $b + $m * $w1;
$w2 = $w1 + random(20, 80, 5);
$c2 = $b + $m * $w2;

$linear_model = Compute("$m*w + $b");

@opts =
    ('dollars', 'dollars per kilogram', 'kilograms', 'kilograms per dollar');

$slope_dd = DropDown(~~@opts, 1);

$intercept_dd = DropDown(~~@opts, 0);

BEGIN_PGML

The monthly charge for a waste collection service is [$c1] dollars
for [$w1] kg of waste and [$c2] dollars for [$w2] kg of waste.


a) Find a linear model for the cost, [`C`], of waste collection as a function of the number of kilograms, [`w`].

    [` C= `] [_]{$linear_model}

b) What is the slope of the line found in part (a)?

    Slope = [_]{Real($m)}

    What are the units of the slope? [_]{$slope_dd}

c) What is the value of the vertical intercept of the line found in
part (a)?

    Value= [_]{Real($b)}

    The units of the intercept can be interpreted as [_]{$intercept_dd}

END_PGML

$dw = $w2 - $w1;

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
a) We find the slope [`m`] and intercept [`b`] in the linear equation
[`C = b + m w`]. To find the slope [`m`], we use

[```m=\frac{\Delta C}{\Delta w} =\frac{[$c2]-[$c1]}{[$w2]-[$w1]}=[$m]```].

We substitute to find b:

[```[$c2] = b + ([$m])([$dw]) ```]

so that [`b = [$b]`].

The linear formula is [`C = [$m] w + [$b]`].


b) The slope is [`[$m]`] dollars per kilogram. Each additional kilogram
of waste costs [`[$m]`] dollars.

c) The intercept is [`[$b]`] dollars. The flat monthly fee to subscribe
to the waste collection is [`[$b]`] dollars, even if there is no waste.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();
